SIMPLE: equal
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Equal
<hw>E"qual</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>aequalis</ets>, fr. <ets>aequus</ets> even, equal; akin to Skr.
<ets><?/ka</ets>, and perh. to L. <ets>unus</ets> for older
<ets>oinos</ets> one, E. <ets>one</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Agreeing in quantity, size, quality, degree, value, etc.; having
the same magnitude, the same value, the same degree, etc.; -- applied to
number, degree, quantity, and intensity, and to any subject which admits
of them; neither inferior nor superior, greater nor less, better nor
worse; corresponding; alike; <as>as, <ex>equal</ex> quantities of land,
water, etc.</as> ; houses of <xex>equal</xex> size; persons of
<xex>equal</xex> stature or talents; commodities of <xex>equal</xex>
value.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Bearing a suitable relation; of just proportion;
having competent power, abilities, or means; adequate; <as>as, he is not
<ex>equal</ex> to the task</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Scots trusted not their own numbers as <qex>equal</qex> to
fight with the English.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is not permitted to me to make my commendations
<qex>equal</qex> to your merit.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose voice an <qex>equal</qex> messenger⟦br⟧
Conveyed thy meaning mild.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not variable; equable; uniform; even; <as>as, an
<ex>equal</ex> movement</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An <xex>equal</xex>
temper.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Evenly balanced; not unduly inclining to either
side; characterized by fairness; unbiased; impartial; equitable;
just.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Are not my ways <qex>equal</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Ezek. xviii.
29.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thee, O Jove, no <qex>equal</qex> judge I deem.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor think it <qex>equal</qex> to answer deliberate reason with
sudden heat and noise.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Of the same interest or concern;
indifferent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They who are not disposed to receive them may let them alone or
reject them; it is <qex>equal</qex> to me.</q>
<rj><qau>Cheyne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Intended for voices of one kind
only, either all male or all female; -- opposed to
<contr>mixed</contr>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Exactly agreeing with respect to
quantity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Equal temperament</b></col>. <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Temperament</er>.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Even; equable; uniform; adequate; proportionate;
commensurate; fair; just; equitable.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Equal
<hw>E"qual</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One not inferior or
superior to another; one having the same or a similar age, rank,
station, office, talents, strength, or other quality or condition; an
equal quantity or number; <as>as, ⟦ldquo⟧If <ex>equals</ex> be taken
from <ex>equals</ex> the remainders are equal</as>.⟦rdquo⟧</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those who were once his <qex>equals</qex> envy and defame him.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>State of being equal; equality.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Equal
<hw>E"qual</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Equaled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Equalled</conjf>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Equaling</conjf> or
<conjf>Equalling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be or become
equal to; to have the same quantity, the same value, the same degree or
rank, or the like, with; to be commensurate with.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On me whose all not <qex>equals</qex> Edward's moiety.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make equal return to; to recompense
fully.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who answered all her cares, and <qex>equaled</qex> all her
love.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make equal or equal to; to equalize; hence, to
compare or regard as equals; to put on equality.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He would not <qex>equal</qex> the mind that he found in himself to
the infinite and incomprehensible.</q> <rj><qau>Berkeley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>equalised</ent>⟦br⟧
